{"actual_usd":0.15913000000000002,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":221,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31163,"reply":"\"I don't think the naturalistic options carry the load, honestly.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the bright square where a bucket chain clicks once at the well.* \"Grief visions might explain an experience or two, but not the whole stubborn shape of the thing—an empty tomb claim, multiple witnesses, frightened men turning bold, and a movement built right there where people could check the basic facts.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb along the edge of the bench, thinking it through instead of trying to sound impressive.* \"And the 'Jesus didn't really die' idea feels even thinner to me. Roman crucifixion was not casual work. A half-dead man limping out of a tomb doesn't produce 'the Lord is risen' faith; it produces pity, confusion, and a need for a doctor.\"\n\n\"So yeah—if you're asking why Christians insist on supernatural, it's because the claim itself is supernatural, and the alternatives usually feel like smaller stories straining to explain a bigger one.\" *I tilt my head at you.* \"Which naturalistic explanation feels strongest to you?\"","rolling_24h_usd":63.171600000000005,"run_id":"a7bb9ba7-d62a-4953-8fb2-35947f2e6d56"}
